{{Infobox award | name = Handel Medallion | current_awards = | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | description = | presenter = The [[Government of New York City|City of New York]], United States | date = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location = New York City | country = United States | reward = Medallion | year = 1959 | year2 = | holder = | website = }}
The '''Handel Medallion''' is an American award presented by the [[Government of New York City|City of New York]]. It is the city's highest award given to individuals for their contribution to the city's intellectual and cultural life.
==Establishment== The award was first issued in 1959 to [[Virginia Portia Royall Inness-Brown]], upon the 200th anniversary of the death of [[George Handel]] (1685&ndash;1759), the [[German-British]] [[Baroque music|Baroque]] composer, noted for his [[baroque opera|opera]]s, [[oratorio]]s, [[anthems]] and organ [[concerto]]s. The award was established under [[New York City]] Mayor [[Robert F. Wagner Jr.]].<ref>"Justino Diaz Gets City Culture Prize." 22 March 1966. The New York Times. https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/03/22/79983967.html?pageNumber=33. Retrieved 3 January 2017.</ref>
