'''James Whatman Bosanquet''' (1804–1877) was an English banker and writer on biblical chronology.

==Life==
He was son of the banker Samuel Bosanquet (1768–1843) and his wife Laetitia Philippa Whatman of Kent, born 10 January 1804; Samuel Richard Bosanquet was his elder brother.<ref name="ODNB">{{cite ODNB|id=2928|title=Bosanquet, James Whatman|first=Anita|last=McConnell}}</ref> He was educated at [[Westminster School]], and at the age of 18 entered Bosanquet, Salt, & Co., the family bank. In due course he became a partner.<ref name="DNB">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bosanquet, James Whatman|volume=5}}</ref>

A contributor to the ''Transactions of the Society of Biblical Archæology'', Bosanquet subsidised its publication; and he also supported other works on [[Assyriology]]. He died 22 December 1877.<ref name="DNB"/>

==Works==
Bosanquet was known as a writer on biblical and Assyrian chronology:<ref name="DNB"/>

*''Chronology of the Times of Daniel, Ezra, and Nehemiah'' (1848);
*''Fall of Nineveh and the Siege of Sennacherib, chronologically considered'' (1853); 
*''Messiah the Prince, or the Inspiration of the Prophecies of Daniel'' (1856, 2nd edition 1869); 
*''Hebrew Chronology from Solomon to Christ'' (1867);
*''Chronological Remarks on Assurbanipal'' (1871);’ and 
*''On the Date of Lachish'' (1878).

His earliest publications, related to finance, were ''Metallic, Paper, and Credit Currency'', 1842, and a ''Letter to the Right Hon. G. Cornewall Lewis on the Bank Charter Act of 1844'', 1857.<ref name="DNB"/>

==Family==
Bosanquet married three times:<ref name="ODNB"/>

#To Merelina, daughter of [[Sir Nicholas Conyngham Tindal]] (five sons, three daughters);
#To Frances Georgiana Elizabeth (c.1817–1862), daughter of [[Lord John Thomas Henry Somerset]] (no children); and
#To Emily Dorothy Best (three daughters).

[[Bernard Bosanquet (cricketer)|Bernard Bosanquet]] the cricketer was a grandson.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=56669|title=Bosanquet, Bernard James Tindal|first=Glenys|last=Williams}}</ref>

