{{Infobox ancient site |name = Khirbat al-Minya |native_name = |alternate_name = Ayn Minyat Hisham, Hurvat Minim |image = Minya.jpg |alt = 200px |caption = The ruins of the Minya palace, 2009 |map_type = Israel |map_alt = |map_size = 200 |location = |region = |coordinates = {{coord|32.864884|35.536223|display=inline}} |grid_position =200/252 [[Palestine grid|PAL]] |type = palace |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder =[[Umayyad]] ruler |material = |built = 8th century |abandoned = 8th century, later reused |epochs = |cultures = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = |condition = |ownership = |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }}
'''Khirbat al-Minya''' (also known as '''Ayn Minyat Hisham''' or '''Hurvat Minim''') is an [[Umayyad]]-built palace in the eastern [[Galilee]], [[Israel]], located about {{convert|200|m|ft|sp=us}} west of the northern end of [[Sea of Galilee|Lake Tiberias]].<ref name="Singh">{{Cite book|title=International Encyclopaedia of Islamic Dynasties|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HtK9nRgBnE4C&pg=PA227&dq=Khirabat+Minya|first=Nagendra Kumar|last=Singh|publisher=Anmol Publications PVT LTD|year=2000|isbn= 9788126104031 |page=227}}</ref> It was erected as a ''[[Ksar|qasr]]'' complex, with a palace, mosque, and bath built by a single patron.<ref name="Necipogulu">{{cite book|title=Muqarnas, Volume 13: An Annual on the Visual Culture of the Islamic World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NdCTI5FqayAC&pg=PA35&dq=Khirbat+Minya|first=Gulru|last=Necipogulu|publisher=Brill|year=1996|isbn= 9789004106338 |page=35}}</ref>
The site is the only Umayyad ruin in Israeli territory with remains above the ground and features one of the earliest mosques in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].
==History==
===Construction=== Khirbat al-Minya was likely built during the reign of the Umayyad caliph [[al-Walid I]] (705-715 [[Common Era|CE]]) and an inscription on a stone found at the site mentions his name. The supposed patron of the palace was al-Walid's son 'Umar ibn al-Walid, who served as the governor of [[Tiberias]] during his father's reign, but fell out of favor when his uncle [[Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik]] assumed the role of caliph.<ref name="Necipogulu"/> This makes the palace's mosque one of the earliest to be built in Palestine.<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |16}}
[[File:Decoration at Umayyad Palace at Khirbat ul Minya-6.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Decorations from the Minya palace]] Khirbat al-Minya served a number of purposes, including as local administrative center for a subregion of the [[Jund al-Urdunn]] ("District of Jordan") and as a contact point for 'Umar and local [[Arab tribes]]. It also could have served as a caravanserai for merchants traveling along the Sea of Galilee or northeast from the lake shore to the coast. Another purpose of Khirbat al-Minya was a winter retreat for the governor of Tiberias or an alternative for the traditional summer retreat for the governor at [[Baysan]].<ref name="Necipogulu"/>
Khirbat al-Minya was abandoned at an uncertain date, but was later temporarily resettled.<ref name="Singh"/> There is evidence that the palace was in use until at least the end of the Umayyad period in 750 CE. A strong earthquake hit the region, probably in the [[749 Galilee earthquake]]. This damaged the building, causing a rift to run through the eastern wing, going straight through the mosque's [[mihrab]]. The damage in the niche were never repaired. It thus remains uncertain whether the palace was ever finished: Fallen debris from the earthquake was discovered in the 20th century in situ on the floor tiles of the main entry. The unused raw materials of a mosaic builder were found in the antechamber of the mosque.<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |17}}
Moreover, based on the stratification established in the western part of the site and the discovery of [[Mamluk]] pottery in 1959, the palace was settled again during the late [[Mamluk]] period (14th-15th centuries).<ref name="Singh"/><ref name="Petersen150">{{cite book|title=Dictionary of Islamic Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gVQj7bW0W9MC&pg=RA1-PA150&dq=Khirbat+Minya|first=Andrew|last=Petersen|publisher=Routledge|year=2002|isbn= 9780203203873 |page=150}}</ref> It is likely that the building was used as a [[Caravanserai|khan]] in this period, due to its position at a cross-road between the main Damascus-Cairo ([[Via Maris]]) route and a secondary route to [[Safad]] via Khan [[Jubb Yusuf]]. A Khan al-Minya was constructed 300 m due north of the palace by [[Tankiz|Saif al-Din Tankiz]] (reigned 1312-1340), the Mamluk governor of Syria, during the reign of [[Al-Nasir Muhammad]].<ref>Khalidi, 1992, p. 542</ref><ref name="peterson2002b">Petersen, 2001, pp. 220–222</ref><ref name="Hastingsp97">{{cite book|title=A Dictionary of Christ and the Gospels: Volume II (Part One -- Labour - Profession)|first=James|last=Hastings|publisher=The Minerva Group, Inc.|year=2004|isbn= 9781410217875|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t4-BHh24QbwC&pg=PA97&dq=mejdel&q=mejdel |page=97}}</ref> Parts of Khirbat al-Minya might have been used as building material for the new khan; baked bricks and a marble capital found during excavations of the khan were assumed to be taken from the palace.<ref name="peterson2002b"/>
In 1596 it appeared under the name of ''Mina (Minya)'' in the [[Ottoman Syria|Ottoman]] [[Defter|tax registers]] as part of the ''[[nahiya]]'' (subdistrict) of Jira in the ''[[Sanjak]]'' (district) of [[Safad]]. It had an all [[Muslim]] population, consisting of 110 households and 2 bachelors, all [[Muslim]]. They paid a fixed tax rate of 25 % on agricultural products, such as wheat, barley, vegetable and fruit garden, orchard, special products, beehives, water buffaloes, in addition to occasional revenues, marked toll and a water mill; totalling 26,476 [[akçe]]. All of the revenue went to a [[waqf]] for [[Madrasa]] ''Tahiriyya'' in [[Quds]] Sarif.<ref>Hütteroth and Abdulfattah, 1977, p. 176</ref><ref>Note that Rhode, 1979, p. [https://www.academia.edu/2026845/The_Administration_and_Population_of_the_Sancak_of_Safed_in_the_Sixteenth_Century 6] writes that the register that Hütteroth and Abdulfattah studied was not from 1595/6, but from 1548/9</ref>
Parts of the ruin were used as a water reservoir (likely for a mill) and later a large brick oven was built in the south wing and used to process sugar cane from nearby plantations. In the 19th century locals built huts on the rubble heaps.<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |17}}
===Modern rediscovery=== In the second half of the 19th century, [[Charles William Wilson]] and other European travelers discovered ancient ruins among the huts of a local [[Fellah]] settlement. Some thought it to be [[Capernaum]], where according to the New Testament [[Jesus]] had taught at the local [[synagogue]]. This was likely an argument for the purchase of the area along with nearby Tell el-Oreme, by the ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Deutscher Verein vom Heiligen Lande|de}}'', a Catholic society from Germany, in 1895. After the true Capernaum synagogue was discovered in 1904, Andreas Evaristus Mader (1881-1949), an archeologist and [[Salvatorians|Salvatorian patre]] conducted exploratory excavations at the ruin and its environments on behalf of the [[Görres Society]] in 1911-4 and again in 1931. Identifying a large quadratic structure with outer walls and corner towers, he thought it to be a Roman fort or [[castrum]].<ref name = "AID">{{cite magazine|last=Kuhnen|first=Hans-Peter|title=Denkmal der Glaubensgeschichte im Heiligen Land| newspaper = Archäologie in Deutschland|date=February 2016| language = de |publisher=WBG|pages=14–19}}</ref>{{rp |14}}
[[File:Horvat Minya Visit, Israel 04.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A section of a wall from Minya palace]]
This was corrected by further work by {{Interlanguage link multi|Alfons Maria Schneider|de}} and {{Interlanguage link multi|Oswin Puttrich-Reignard|de}} in 1932-9. The outbreak of [[World War II]] terminated German archaeological work in Palestine. At that point, Schneider and Puttrich-Reignard had excavated about half of the palace and published some of their findings. By 1937, they had uncovered the mosque and it had become obvious that the building was an early Islamic palace. The findings were evenly distributed between the ''[[Museum für Islamische Kunst (Berlin)|Museum für Islamische Kunst]]'' at [[Berlin]] and the Palestine Archaeological Museum in [[Jerusalem]] (today the [[Rockefeller Museum]]). Whilst most of the findings left in Palestine have today been lost, the Berlin pieces remain in the care of the [[Prussian Cultural Heritage Foundation]], and some of them are exhibited in the museum's permanent exhibition. The notes and drawings from the excavations are likewise kept in Berlin and have been the subject of recent studies by archaeologists from the universities of Berlin and Bamberg.<ref name="Singh"/><ref name="AID"/>{{rp |14–15}}<ref>Puttrich-Reignard, O. (1938), Puttrich-Reignard, O. (1939). Cited in Petersen, 2001b, p. 220</ref>
During July–August 1959, the western section of the palace was excavated by [[Oleg Grabar|O. Grabar]] in collaboration with the [[Israel Antiquities Authority]].<ref name="Singh"/> In 1960 the site was excavated by an Israeli-American expedition, intending to refine the chronology and the plan of the palace.<ref>Grabar et al. (1960). Cited in Petersen, 2002b, p.220.</ref> Several rescue digs were later conducted by the Israeli Antiquities Authority in the environments of the palace, revealing a bath from [[Late Antiquity|late antiquity]]/early Islamic times (1963), a medieval caravanserai (1988) and the remains of a medieval settlement between the palace and the lake (2011).<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |15}}
With the reproachment between Israel and Germany in the 1960s, the ''Verein'' was reinstated as owner but handed over its rights to the palace itself to the [[Israel Nature and Parks Authority]], which awarded the area protected status as a listed monument and has since been responsible for the palace's upkeep.<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |15}}
In 2000, it was proposed that Khirbat al-Minya should become a [[World Heritage Site]].<ref>[http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1474/ Horvat Minnim], Suggestion to have Khirbat al-Minya recognized as a UNESCO world heritage site, in 2000.</ref>
In 2001, a study by the [[Getty Conservation Institute]] found severe structural damage to the ruin, caused by the climate and by vegetation. A lack of funds has since prevented countermeasures as well as investment in making the area more accessible to visitors.<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |15–16}}
==Architecture== [[File:Sockel.JPG|thumb|right|The base of Khirbat al-Minya, showing the limestone blocks laid over a lower [[Course (architecture)|course]] of black basalt stones]]
The palace of Khirbat al-Minya is contained within an irregular rectangular enclosure (66 by 73 meters) oriented north-south,<ref name="Petersen150"/> facing the four cardinal points.<ref name="Singh"/><ref name="Petersen150"/> Like other Umayyad palaces it has round towers at its corners and semi-circular towers in the middle of each wall except the eastern wall where a monumental entrance was located.<ref name="Necipogulu"/> The main gate in the middle of the eastern wall is formed by two projecting half-round towers separated by the arch of the gateway.<ref name="Petersen150"/>
The center of the structure is occupied by a colonnaded courtyard with twin staircases giving access to an upper floor level.<ref name="Petersen150"/> The rooms which surrounded the courtyard differ in size and arrangement and included a mosque, numerous rooms with mosaics, and a throne room.<ref name="Singh"/><ref name="Necipogulu"/> The mosque is located in the southeastern corner and is divided into twelve bays supported on piers. Next to the mosque is a triple-aisled basilica hall. Like other Umayyad desert or country palaces, such as [[Qasr al-Heer al-Gharbi]] in the [[Syrian Desert]] and [[Khirbat al-Mafjar]] near [[Jericho]], Khirbat al-Minya followed the Umayyad model of a five-room ''bait'' ("house"),<ref>{{cite book|title=The idea and ideal of the town between late Antiquity and the early Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_ti9poThbwEC&pg=PA86&dq=Khirbat+Minya|first=[[G. P. Brogiolo|Gian Pietro]] |last=[[G. P. Brogiolo|Brogiolo]]|first2=Bryan|last2=Ward-Perkins|publisher=Brill|year=1999|isbn= 9789004109018 |page=71}}</ref> flanking the basilica hall.<ref name="Singh"/> To the north are the residential quarters.<ref name="Petersen150"/>
The building is constructed of finely dressed [[limestone]] blocks laid in regular courses with a lower course of black [[basalt]] stones.<ref name="Petersen150"/> The mosque had a simple decoration, but the domed gateway chamber and the southern rooms were richly decorated.<ref name="Singh"/> The top of the walls were decorated with large stepped [[merlon]]s and the interior was decorated with a variety of glass and stone mosaics.<ref name="Petersen150"/> Marble panels covered the dadoes of the walls and stone mosaics combined with glass cubes were set in geometric carpet-like patterns on the floors of the five southern rooms. A well-preserved floor mosaic has been discovered in the western part of the palace.<ref name="Singh"/> Based on the foundations of the gate house, parts of the palace were at least 15 metres high.<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |16}}
==Today== The Israel Nature and Park Authority has erected a sign at the site which states that the protected monument was an early Islamic palace built by [[Al-Walid I]] or [[Al-Walid II]]. Its unique status, as the only Umayyad-built palace with remains above the ground in Israel, has resulted in efforts to maintain and restore the ruins and to make them more accessible to visitors. In 2012, the ''Institut für Vor-und Frühgeschichte'' of the University of Mainz, in cooperation with the ''Deutscher Verein vom Heiligen Lande'' presented a plan to the Israeli authorities. A guide was published and with financial support from the German Foreign Ministry, the University is currently working with the National Park Authority and the Israel Antiques Authority to protect the masonry from further damage.<ref name="AID"/>{{rp |16,18–19}}
